THE DECREASE IN NET PERIODIC PENSION BENEFIT COST OF

$2,263 MILLION

IN

2016

IS PRIMARILY DUE TO LOWER SERVICE COSTS AND LOWER AMORTIZATION OF ACTUARIAL LOSSES. THE LOWER SERVICE COSTS REFLECT THE CHANGES TO OUR RETIREMENT PLANS WHEREBY CERTAIN EMPLOYEES TRANSITIONED IN 2016 TO A COMPANY-FUNDED DEFINED CONTRIBUTION RETIREMENT SAVINGS PLAN. THE LOWER AMORTIZATION OF ACTUARIAL LOSSES REFLECTS ACTUARIAL GAINS IN 2015 RESULTING FROM THE YEAR-END DISCOUNT RATE INCREASE FROM 3.9% TO 4.2%.

